Problem and Hypothesis
Question: Can the results of a baseball season be predicted in advance, using
player and team statistics?
Goals and hypothesis: Using data from previous major league baseball
season, I want to predict the results of the 2015 baseball season. I am not
concerned about the playoffs, as these are generally agreed to be highly
statistically variable and unpredictable, due to the fact that they a) teams are not
fairly selected to enter the playoffs, as a team is measured only against their
division rather against their league as a whole and b) there are so few games
played in the playoff season relative to the regular season that there is too much
statistical variability and a high randomness factor.
Thus, the goal of my project is to predict the ranks of the 30 teams at the end of
the regular season. This means, simply, where will one team stand relative to all
other 29 teams, according to their number of wins per number of games
played? My hypothesis is that the results of one season can be predicted using
statistical classification/correlation methods using data from previous seasons.

Phase 4: Regression ->
Prediction
LINEAR REGRESSION
Using a linear regression classifier, I attempted to predict seasonal standings using the data from 1985-2013 as
the training data (just using salaries and batting stats no pitching). The independent values, or feature set, are
the features found in the previous set i.e. average player salary, average player RBI, etc.
The dependent values, or attempted target values, are the standings at the end of the season, or the team ranks
by their average number of wins per games played. We want to predict, using the data from the training set, the
standings for the 2014 season (or 2015 season, although we wont know if thats accurate until the end of 2015
summer).
As it turns out, it is almost impossible to use these a single statistical variable (i.e. player salary) to predict the
results of a season.
But the question is, can we use combinations of variables to accurately predict? What about the combined datasets
of salary and player RBI?
Mean accuracy in predicting 2014 season results using training
data: 0.0394957138285
This is extremely low accuracy, indicating that there is too much
randomness in the data to form an accurate prediction.

Phase 5: Results
Keep in mind that ranks are not ordered intuitively; the higher the rank, the worse the team did. In other words, the closer
the team is to the #1 position (lower rank) the better they did.
Analysis:
Why these results? Some of them seem intuitive. For example, a higher RBI is correlated with a lower rank, suggesting that
players who were selected for their ability to score runs helped lead the team to a better standing.
But what about RBI-ERA? This shows a positive correlation, indicating that the combined high-RBI-high-ERA stats lead to a
worse ranking. This suggests that ERA matters than RBI in predicting the teams final standings. But it seems like runs-
batted-in should matter equally to earned-run-average. A possible explanation here is the rookie factor: my data does not
include prior stats for rookies, since they have no prior stats (or at least, minor league stats were not part of this dataset).
Pitchers with more experience (less likely to be rookies) tend to be the ones who open most games, but batters can often be
rookies. Thus, the RBI factor may be skewed somewhat since we dont know how well these rookies performed.
You may notice that the correlations involving the feature salary seem less intuitive. My model did not account for inflation
over the years. Ideally, I should have used RELATIVE salary, rather than absolute how much more are Yankees players
making relative to As players? However, this would have taken several extra steps and so I stuck with absolute salary, but
that means that the salary statistic is likely very skewed.
Similar analysis can be used on the other stats, as some of them tend to be more intuitive than others. Included in the
Pearson correlation chart are only the results of highest correlation some of the other statistics showed hardly any
correlation with final ranking. Interestingly enough, the lowest correlations (meaning no correlation shown) appear for the
relationship between rank and salary, and rank and home runs. That does not seem intuitive, at least for the home runs
statistic. Perhaps even while home runs are flashy and clearly beneficial, they are not the actual highest contributors to the
teams abilities. There does sometimes seem to be a trend that the strongest batters strike out the most, because the aim
for power more than accuracy. As for salary, this could be interpreted to mean that teams who spend the most dont do as
well, but I suspect its because salaries werent adjusted for inflation in this model, so therefore their stats are highly skewed.
